snippet.textDisplay:
Based on the information given in this video, I'm inclined to opt for the AstraZenica-Oxford
vaccine. One very important point you made, was that the other two vaccines may only
prevent symptoms of the disease, and not prevent infection, whereas the Oxford vaccine may
prevent both. And now, I want to raise another subject relative to vaccines, and SARS-CoV-2:
In a peer-reviewed article published in the American Journal of Microbiology, the authors presented strong associative evidence that vaccination with the MMR 11 (Measles, Mumps, Rubella) vaccine, can offer up to 70% protection against infection with the SARS-CoV-2 virus.
This happens because the viral signatures of those three viruses are quite similar to the the viral signature of the SARS-CoV-2 virus. The immune system of a person who has received the MMR 11 vaccine, recognizes the SARS-CoV-2 virus, because of that similarity to the other viruses, and attacks the SARS virus. Has your organization become aware of this research, and if so, will you address it, in a video?
